  <fr:p>Let <fr:tex>a \in  A</fr:tex> be an element of the dcpo <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>. To show that <fr:tex>\eta _A a</fr:tex> is positive, we fix a semidirected subset <fr:tex>U \subseteq   \mathsf { L } {A}</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>\eta _A a \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup  U</fr:tex> to show that <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> is inhabited. The inequality implies that <fr:tex>\top \sqsubseteq   \exists  u \in  U. u{ \downarrow }</fr:tex>, so we know that <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> is inhabited.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>Conversely, suppose that <fr:tex>u \in \mathsf { L } {A}</fr:tex> is a positive element. Let <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> be the semidirected family <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left \{ v  \mid  v = u  \land  u \downarrow \right \} \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>; we evidently have <fr:tex>u \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup {U}</fr:tex>, so <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> is inhabited. Thus it follows that <fr:tex>u</fr:tex> is defined.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
